er;\"|7\n|-\n|''(various writers)''\n|United States\n|'' 50 Years of Great Recordings''\n|2005\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|*\n|-\n|''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]''\n|United States\n|''51 Albums representing a Generation, a Sound and a Movement''\n|2004\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|*\n|-\n|''Vibe''\n|United States\n|''150 Albums That Define the Vibe Era (1992\u20132007)''\n|2007\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|*\n|-\n|''[[Village Voice]]''\n|United States\n|''Albums of the Year''\n|1997\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|12\n|}\n\n== Commercial performance ==\n''Life After Death'' was released to a significant amount of critical praise and commercial success. The album sold 690,000 copies in its first week.<ref>{{cite web|title=Check Out How Biggie's 'Life After Death' Was Made|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2014/03/the-making-of-life-after-death-many-men/|work=XXL |accessdate=April 15, 2014}}</ref> In 2000, the album was certified [[RIAA certification|Diamond]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=tblDiamond |title=RIAA \u2013 Gold & Platinum Database |accessdate=April 15, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130725044833/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=tblDiamond |archivedate=July 25, 2013 }}</ref> denoting shipment of 5 million copies (the threshold for double albums) and it has been credited as one of the best-selling rap albums of all time. It also made the largest jump to number one on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart in history, jumping from number 176 to number one in one week. Also, it spent four weeks at number one on the [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]] chart and topped the [[Billboard Year-End]] chart as a ''Billboard'' 200 for 1997.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/charts/yearend_chart_display.jsp?f=Top+R%26B/Hip-Hop+Albums&g=Year-end+Albums&year=1997 |title=Information Not Found |website=Billboard.com |date= |accessdate=February 28, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy and influence ==\nAlthough released in the wake of B.I.G.'s fatal shooting, ''Life After Death'' signaled a stylistic change in [[gangsta rap]] as it crossed over to the commercial mainstream. After the release of ''Life After Death'', [[Puff Daddy]]'s [[Bad Boy Records]] continued to bring pop and gangsta rap closer together: the references to violence and drug dealing remained, as did the entire \"gangsta\" rhetoric, but the overall production style changed from the previously darker sound to a cleaner, [[Sampling (music)|sample]]-heavy, more upbeat sound that was directly fashioned for the mainstream pop charts, as seen in the single \"[[Mo Money Mo Problems]]\". The Notorious B.I.G. is often credited with initiating this transition, as he was among the first mainstream rappers to produce albums with a calculated attempt to include both gritty and realistic gangsta narratives as well as more radio-friendly productions. The majority of the album was produced by [[Stevie J|Steven \"Stevie J\" Jordan]], [[Deric \"D-Dot\" Angelettie]], Carlos \"July Six\" Broady, [[Ron \"Amen-Ra\" Lawrence|Ron Lawrence]], and Nashiem Myrick. However, other notable hip-hop producers such as [[Easy Mo Bee]], [[Havoc (Mobb Deep)|Havoc]] from [[Mobb Deep]], [[DJ Premier]] and [[RZA]] from [[Wu-Tang Clan]] contributed beats to the album as well.\n\nVarious artists were specifically influenced by songs on ''Life After Death''. [[Evidence (artist)|Evidence]]'s \"Down in New York City\" is essentially \"Going Back to Cali\" from the perspective of a [[West Coast hip hop]] artist. [[Jay-Z]] borrows four bars from \"The World Is Filled...\" in his song \"[[I Just Wanna Love U (Give It 2 Me)]]\", as well as the chorus from his song \"Squeeze 1st\" from \"[[Hypnotize (The Notorious B.I.G. song)|Hypnotize]]\", a line in \"The Ruler's Back\" from \"Kick in the Door\" and \"You're Nobody ('Til Somebody Kills You)\" on \"[[D.O.A. (Death of Auto-Tune)]]\". [[Ice Cube]] borrows the chorus from \"Kick in the Door\" for his song \"Child Support\". As with B.I.G.'s \"I Love The Dough\" [[Monica (entertainer)|Monica]]'s 2010 song \"[[Everything to Me (Monica song)|Everything to Me]]\" samples \"I Love You More\" by [[Ren\u00e9 & Angela]]. The official remix includes a verse from B.I.G. that originally appeared on \"I Love The Dough\". [[SWV]] sampled \"Ten Crack Commandments\" on the opening track \"Someone\" featuring B.I.G.'s former protege and friend [[Sean Combs|Puff Daddy]]. The French rapper [[Rohff]] named his album \"La Vie Avant La Mort\" (Life Before Death) (2001) as a tribute to B.I.G, [[Joey Badass]] interpolated the lines 'Kick in the Door' on \"Super Predator\" from ''[[All-Amerikkkan Badass]]'' (2017). The album has sold 350,000 copies.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n== Track listing ==\nCredits adapted from ''Life After Death'' liner notes.<ref name=\"booklet\">[http://www.rapmusicguide.com/item/11184/Notorious_B.I.G._Life_After_Death.html Notorious B.I.G. \u2013 Life After Death: 1st Press. CD]</ref>\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = \n| headline = Disc one\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| title17 = \n| length17 = \n| title18 = \n| length18 = \n| title19 = \n| length19 = \n| title20 = \n| length20 = \n| total_length = 61:18\n| title1 = Life After Death Intro\n| writer1 = {{flat list|\n*[[The Notorious B.I.G.|Christopher Wallace]]\n*[[Sean Combs]]\n*[[Stevie J|Steven Jordan]]}}\n| extra1 = {{flat list|\n*Sean \"Puffy\" Combs\n*[[Stevie J]].\n*[[The Notorious B.I.G.]]{{ref|a|[a]}}}}\n| length1 = 1:39\n| title2 = Somebody's Gotta Die\n| writer2 = {{flat list|\n*Wallace\n*Nashiem Myrick\n*Carlos Broady\n*Combs\n*[[The Dramatics|Anthony Hester]]}}\n| extra2 = {{flat list|\n*Myrick\n*Carlos \"July Six\" Broady\n*Combs}}\n| length2 = 4:26\n| title3 = [[Hypnotize (The Notorious B.I.G. song)|Hypnotize]]\n| writer3 = {{flat list|\n*Wallace\n*Combs\n*Deric Angelettie\n*[[Ron \"Amen-Ra\" La