:Bad Boy Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by KayGee]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Buckwild]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Sean Combs]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Clark Kent (producer)]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by DJ Premier]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Easy Mo Bee]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Havoc (musician)]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by RZA]]\n[[Category:Mafioso rap albums]]\n[[Category:Concept albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Life After Death\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[The Notorious B.I.G.]]\n| cover      = NotoriousB.I.G.LifeAfterDeath.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|1997|3|25|mf=y}}\n| recorded   = September 1995 \u2013 January 1997\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Gangsta rap]]<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.cnn.com/SHOWBIZ/9704/11/rap.sales/index.html |title= Gangsta rap revels in \"Life After Death\" |work= [[CNN]] |date= April 11, 1997 |accessdate= November 26, 2019}}</ref>|[[mafioso rap]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Sidney Madden|url=https://www.xxlmag.com/news/2015/03/today-hip-hop-notorious-b-g-drops-life-death/|title=Today in Hip-Hop: The Notorious B.I.G. Drops \u2018Life After Death\u2019 Album|publisher=[[XXL Magazine]]|date=2015-03-25|accessdate=2019-11-23}}</ref>|[[hardcore hip hop]]<ref>{{cite web|author=MTV News Staff|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/620890/biggie-lp-first-hardcore-diamond-album/|title=BIGGIE LP FIRST HARDCORE DIAMOND ALBUM|publisher=[[MTV News]]|date=2000-02-01|accessdate=2019-11-23}}</ref>\n}}\n| length     = 120:39\n| label      = {{plainlist|\n* [[Bad Boy Records|Bad Boy]]\n* [[Arista Records|Arista]]}}\n| producer   = {{plainlist|\n* [[The Hitmen (production team)|The Hitmen]]\n* [[Buckwild]]\n* [[Clark Kent (producer)|Clark Kent]]\n* [[Sean \"Puffy\" Combs]]\n* [[DJ Enuff]]\n* [[DJ Premier]]\n* [[Stevie J]]\n* [[Easy Mo Bee]]\n* [[Havoc (musician)|Havoc]]\n* Jiv Pos\n* [[Daron Jones]]\n* [[KayGee]]\n* [[Notorious B.I.G.]]\n* Paragon\n* [[RZA]]\n}}\n| prev_title = [[Ready to Die]]\n| prev_year  = 1994\n| next_title = [[Born Again (The Notorious B.I.G. album)|Born Again]]\n| next_year  = 1999\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Life After Death\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Hypnotize (The Notorious B.I.G. song)|Hypnotize]]\n | single1date = March 1, 1997\n | single2     = [[Mo Money Mo Problems]]\n | single2date = July 11, 1997\n | single3     = [[Sky's the Limit (The Notorious B.I.G. song)|Sky's the Limit]]\n | single3date = November 14, 1997\n}}\n}}\n'''''Life After Death''''' is the second and final [[studio album]] by American rapper [[The Notorious B.I.G.]], released on March 25, 1997, on [[Bad Boy Records]] and [[Arista Records]].<ref>\n*{{cite magazine|title=Today In Hip-Hop History: Notorious B.I.G. Dropped His Posthumous \u2018Life After Death\u2019 LP 22 Years Ago|url=http://thesource.com/2019/03/25/today-in-hip-hop-history-notorious-b-i-g-dropped-his-posthumous-life-after-death-lp-22-years-ago/|magazine=The Source|accessdate=29 May 2019}}\n*{{cite magazine|title=Today in Hip-hop: The Notorious B.I.G. drops 'Life After Death' album |url=https://www.xxlmag.com/news/2015/03/today-hip-hop-notorious-b-g-drops-life-death/|magazine=XXL Magazine|accessdate=29 May 2019}}</ref> A [[double album]], it was released sixteen days after his [[Murder of Christopher Wallace|death]]. It features collaborations with guest artists such as [[112 (band)|112]], [[Jay-Z]], [[Lil' Kim]], [[Mase]], [[Bone Thugs-n-Harmony]], [[Too Short|Too $hort]], [[Angela Winbush]], [[Darryl McDaniels|D.M.C.]] of [[Run-D.M.C.]], [[R. Kelly]], [[The LOX]], and [[Puff Daddy]]. ''Life After Death'' exhibits The Notorious B.I.G. further delving into the [[mafioso rap]] subgenre. The album is a sequel to his first album, ''[[Ready to Die]]'', and picks up where the last song, \"Suicidal Thoughts\", ends.\n\nThe album was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best Rap Album|Best Rap Album]], [[Grammy Award for Best Rap Solo Performance|Best Rap Solo Performance]] for its first single \"[[Hypnotize (The Notorious B.I.G. song)|Hypnotize]]\", and [[Grammy Award for Best Rap Performance by a Duo or Group|Best Rap Performance by a Duo or Group]] for its second single \"[[Mo Money Mo Problems]]\" at the [[40th Annual Grammy Awards]]. In 2012, the album was ranked at No. 476 on ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine's list of \"[[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time]].<ref name=\"500-greatest\">{{cite magazine| url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-156826/elvis-costello-and-the-attractions-armed-forces-44401/| year=2012| title=500 Greatest Albums of All Time Rolling Stone\u2019s definitive list of the 500 greatest albums of all time| magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]| accessdate= September 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nTwo and a half years before the album's release, the Notorious B.I.G. who had married [[Faith Evans]], became East Coast's icon in the East Coast{{endash}}West Coast rivalry and made guest appearances on albums by [[Jay-Z]] and [[Luther Campbell]] amongst others. The album was supposed to be released on [[Halloween]] in 1996, but was pushed back to 1997. Two weeks before its release, on March 9, the Notorious B.I.G. was shot four times in a drive-by shooting and was later pronounced dead at [[Cedars-Sinai Medical Center]] in Los Angeles.\n\n== Feud references and subliminal disses ==\nConflict with other rappers is a major theme throughout the album. Numerous songs contain references to B.I.G.'s rivals, some subtle and some obvious.\n\n=== \"Kick in the Door\" ===\nThe track \"Kick in the Door\" is directed at [[Nas]], [[Jeru the Damaja]], [[Raekwon]], [[Ghostface Killah]] and even the track's producer [[DJ Premier]]. The subtle messages have been speculated on by listeners and confirmed by artists on several occasions, including ''[[XXL Magazine|XXL]]'' magazine's April 2003 edition, \"The Making of: Life After Death\".\n\nIn \"The Making of: Life After Death\", Nashiem Myrick reveals that the second verse has lines directed at [[Jeru the Damaja]] and [[DJ Premier]]:<ref name=\"xxlmag.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/online/?p=405 |title=The Making of Life After Death: Many Men |website=Xxlmag.Com |accessdate=February 28, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100814024642/http://www.xxlmag.com/online/?p=405 |archivedate=August 14, 2010 }}</ref> \"Nas said that record was for him, but when Big said, \"Son, I'm surprised you run with them/I think they got cum in them, 'cause they nothin' but dicks,\" he was talking about Jeru the Damaja to Premo 'cause Jeru was going at Big and Puff and all them [with the Premier-produced \"One Day\" in Jeru's album ''[[Wrath of the Math]]''].\"\n\nThe line \"Fuck that, why try, throw bleach in your eye\" is a reference to Raekwon's jab on the track \"Ice Water\" from ''[[Only Built 4 Cuban Linx...]]'' where Raekwon raps.\n\n<blockquote>\nThat's life, to top it all off, beef with White<br />\npullin bleach out tryin to throw it in my eyesight<br />\n</blockquote>\n\nThe lines on the final verse are directed at Nas as a reference to Nas challenging The Notorious B.I.G. for the title of \"King of New York\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.king-mag.com/online/?p=5357 |title= KING Legacy: Nasir Jones, Part Two |website=KING-mag.com |date=May 1, 2008 |accessdate=February 28, 2012}}</ref> in the song \"[[The Message (Nas song)|The Message]]\" from the album ''[[It Was Written]]'' in which Nas raps:\n\n<blockquote>\nYo let me let y'all niggaz know one thing<br />\nThere's one life, one love, so there can only be one King<br />\n</blockquote>\n\nBiggie struck back with the lines:\n\n<blockquote>\nAin't no other kings in this rap thing<br />\nThey siblings, nothing but my chil'ren<br />\nOne shot, they disappearin'<br />\nIt's ill when MC's used to be on cruddy shit<br />\nTook home ''[[Ready to Die]]'', listened, studied shit<br />\nNow they on some money shit, successful out the blue<br />\n</blockquote>\n\nIn \"The Making of: Life After Death\" article [[Lil' Cease]] explains, \"Big talked about Nas a little bit in that shit. It was the King of New York part, the last verse: \"This goes out for those that chose to use disrespectful views on the King of NY.\" That's when Nas had that freestyle out, where he was like, \"I'll take the crown off the so-called King and lock it down.\" That's when Big had the cover of The Source, and it said, \"The King of New York.\"\"<ref name=\"xxlmag.com\" />\n\n=== \"Long Kiss Goodnight\" ===\nIt was speculated by many listeners that the song \"Long Kiss Goodnight\" contains cryptic insults towards [[2Pac]] and [[Death Row Records]] CEO [[Suge Knight]], although at the time it was never confirmed due to the sensitive nature of both rappers' recent deaths.\n\nHowever, Lil' Cease, Biggie's cousin and a member of Junior M.A.F.I.A. claimed the following in ''XXL'' magazine's April 2003 issue about \"Long Kiss Goodnight\": \"That was about 'Pac. He had some shit at the beginning of that though, nobody heard it, on the reel. We had to change it. It was a little too much. I can't remember what Big said about him, but it was terrible. It couldn't make it. He didn't want to do it. He had some fire. But he didn't want to make it too much. He just wanted to address it and to let nigga know, \"I know what's going on, and I could get wreck if I want to.\" Like, \"If I really wanted to get on ya niggas, I could.\"\"\n\n[[P Diddy|Sean Combs]], however, denies these claims stating, \"Naw, it was just some emcee lyrics. I know people wanna have their imagination, but it was just lyrics. You're hearing it from the horse's mouth. I would tell the truth.\"<ref name=\"xxlmag.com\" />\n\nIn the first verse, the lyric \"Laugh Now, Cry Later\" is allegedly a reference to two tattoos on 2Pac's back.<ref name=\"rapgenius.com\">{{cite web|url=http://rapgenius.com/lyrics/The-notorious-b-i-g/Long-kiss-goodnight |title=The Notorious B.I.G. \u2013 Long Kiss Goodnight Lyrics |website=Rap Genius |date= |accessdate=February 28, 2012}}</ref>\nA line in the first verse is supposedly aimed at Shakur:\n\n<blockquote>\nWhen my men bust you just move with such stamina<br />\nSlugs missed ya, [[I Ain't Mad at Cha]] (We Ain't Mad at Cha)<br />\n</blockquote>\n\nThe last two verses in particular seem to be directed towards Tupac:\n\n<blockquote>\nI'm flaming gats, aimin' at these fuckin' maniacs<br />\nPut my name in raps, what part the game is that?<br />\nLike they hustle backwards<br />\nI smoke Backwoods and Dutchies, ya can't touch me<br />\nTry to rush me, slugs go touchy-touchy<br />\nYou're bleeding lovely with your spirit above me or beneath me<br />\nYour whole life you live sneaky<br />\nNow you rest eternally, sleepy, you burn when you creep me<br />\nRest where the worms and the weak be<br />\n</blockquote>\n<blockquote>\nSlugs hit your chest, tap your spine, flat line<br />\nHeard through the grapevine, you got fucked fo' times<br />\nDamn that three to nine, fucked you up for real though<br />\nSlugs still slow, as for remorse, we feel no<br />\n</blockquote>\n\nThe lines seem to be making reference to Tupac frequently mentioning Biggie ''by name'' in his raps, and allegations spread by [[Wendy Williams]] that he had been raped during his prison term at [[Rikers Island]].<ref name=\"rapgenius.com\" />\nAlthough some fans have interpreted these lines as references to Shakur's murder, XXL Magazine wrote that the song was most likely recorded before 2Pac's death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/homepage-highlight/2010/11/8-subliminal-diss-records-that-no-one-claims/4/ |title=8 Subliminal Diss Records That No One Claims |website=Xxlmag.Com |date= |accessdate=February 28, 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Other references ===\nIn \"Going Back to Cali\" the second verse opens up with Biggie's thoughts on the inter-coastal war and his relationship with the West Coast:\n<blockquote>\nIf I got to choose a coast I got to choose the East<br />\nI live out there, so don't go there<br />\nBut that don't mean a nigga can't rest in the West<br />\nSee some nice breasts in the West<br />\nSmoke some nice sess in the West, y'all niggas is a mess<br />\nThinkin' I'm gon' stop, givin' L.A. props<br />\nAll I got is beef with those that violate me<br />\nI shall annihilate thee<br />\nCase closed\n</blockquote>\n\nIn the song \"[[Notorious Thugs]]\", B.I.G. clearly refers to longtime nemesis [[2Pac]] in the line \"so called beef with you-know-who\", calling the feud between him and Shakur 'bullshit', while [[Bone Thugs-N-Harmony]] (who featured 2Pac on one of their songs the same year) throw jabs at [[Three 6 Mafia]], [[Twista]], [[Crucial Conflict]] and [[Do or Die (group)|Do or Die]].\n\nThe tracks \"What's Beef\" and \"My Downfall\", both of which deal with the subject of feuding, as well as \"Last Day\" and \"You're Nobody (Till Somebody Kills You)\" are also said to contain apparent jabs aimed at his rivals (including Shakur), even though Biggie stated in a ''[[Spin Magazine|Spin]]'' magazine interview that the song \"You're Nobody (Till Somebody Kills You)\" was not directed at Shakur, who at the time had recently been shot.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I4irI6O3Ko8C&pg=RA1-PA68&lpg=RA1-PA68&dq=biggie+spin+magazine&resnum=10&sqi=2#v=onepage&q=biggie%20spin%20magazine |title=SPIN |website=Books.google.com |date= |accessdate=February 28, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n{{Album reviews\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"Birchmeier\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/life-after-death-mw0000176659 |title=Life After Death \u2013 The Notorious B.I.G. |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=November 8, 2009 |last=Birchmeier |first=Jason}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Christgau's Consumer Guide: Albums of the '90s|Christgau's Consumer Guide]]''\n| rev2Score = A<ref name=\"Christgau\">{{cite book |chapter-url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/get_album.php?id=2600 |chapter=Notorious B.I.G.: Life After Death |accessdate=November 8, 2009 |last=Christgau |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Christgau |title=[[Christgau's Consumer Guide: Albums of the '90s]] |publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers]] |year=2000 |isbn=0-312-24560-2}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev3Score = C+<ref name=\"Browne\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.ew.com/article/1997/04/11/album-review-life-after-death |title=Life After Death |journal=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=April 11, 1997 |accessdate=November 8, 2009 |last=Browne |first=David |authorlink=David Browne (journalist)}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite news |title=The Notorious B.I.G.: Life After Death (Bad Boy) |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=March 28, 1997 |last=Glaister |first=Dan}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|4|4}}<ref name=\"Coker\">{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1997-03-26-ca-42095-story.html |title=A Memorable 'Life' on Its Own Merits |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=March 26, 1997 |accessdate=April 6, 2020 |last=Coker |first=Cheo Hodari |authorlink=Cheo Hodari Coker}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev6Score = 8/10<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/reviews/19980101000156reviews.html |title=The Notorious B.I.G. \u2013 Life After Death |journal=[[NME]] |date=April 12, 1997 |accessdate=April 6, 2016 |last=Fadele |first=Dele |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000817191947/http://www.nme.com/reviews/reviews/19980101000156reviews.html |archivedate=August 17, 2000 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev7Score = 9.5/10<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/22946-life-after-death/ |title=The Notorious B.I.G.: Life After Death |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=March 9, 2017 |accessdate=March 9, 2017 |last=Ex |first=Kris}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"DeCurtis\">{{cite journal |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/notoriousbig/albums/album/200792/review/6067339/life_after_death |title=Notorious B.I.G.: Life After Death |journal=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=May 1, 1997 |accessdate=November 8, 2009 |last=DeCurtis |first=Anthony |authorlink=Anthony DeCurtis |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090514055828/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/notoriousbig/albums/album/200792/review/6067339/life_after_death |archivedate=May 14, 2009 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev9Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"Hoard\">{{cite book |title=[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide|The New Rolling Stone Album Guide]] |edition=4th |year=2004 |chapter=The Notorious B.I.G. |last=Sheffield |first=Rob |authorlink=Rob Sheffield |editor1-last=Brackett |editor1-first=Nathan |editor2-last=Hoard |editor2-first=Christian |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |isbn=0-7432-0169-8 |page=[https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/592 592]}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[USA Today]]''\n| rev10Score = {{Rating|3.5|4}}<ref name=\"Jones\">{{cite news |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/USAToday/access/11321257.html?dids=11321257:11321257&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Mar+26%2C+1997&author=Steve+Jones&pub=USA+TODAY&desc='Life+After+Death'+is+a+B.I.G.+classic&pqatl=google |title='Life After Death' is a B.I.G. classic |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=March 26, 1997 |accessdate=October 14, 2011 |last=Jones |first=Steve |page=01.D |url-access=subscription |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306222047/http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/USAToday/doc/408713437.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Mar%2026,%201997&author=Steve%20Jones&pub=USA%20TODAY&edition=&startpage=&desc=%27Life%20After%20Death%27%20is%20a%20B.I.G.%20classic |archivedate=March 6, 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Life After Death'' received widespread critical acclaim from critics upon release. [[Jon Pareles]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' described the album as \"flaunting affluence with a leisurely swagger, midtempo grooves and calmly arrogant raps\".<ref name=\"Pareles\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/03/30/arts/swaggering-in-death-s-face-till-the-end.html |title=Swaggering in Death's Face Till the End |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 30, 1997 |accessdate=November 8, 2009 |last=Pareles |first=Jon |authorlink=Jon Pareles}}</ref> [[Anthony DeCurtis]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine called it a \"conscious continuation of ''[[Ready to Die]]''\", and stated \"''Life After Death'' captures crime's undeniable glamour but doesn't stint on the fear, desperation and irretrievable loss that the streets inevitably exact\".<ref name=\"DeCurtis\" /> [[Cheo Hodari Coker]] from the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' wrote that \"''Life After Death'' reflects both the dark and the heartfelt sides of the rapper's [[Gemini (astrology)|Gemini]] personality. It's not only a complex testament to who he was in his private life, but also a demonstration of his amazing rhyming ability. In key moments, B.I.G. does a marvelous job of surfing between accessible music fare tailored for the radio, and more challenging material that will be savored by hard-core rap fans who have long admired B.I.G.'s microphone skills. Rarely has a rapper attempted to please so many different audiences and done it so brilliantly\".<ref name=\"Coker\" /> In a [[The Source#The Source's Five-Mic albums|five-mic]] review for ''[[The Source (magazine)|The Source]]'', Michael A. Gonzales felt that it would \"undoubtedly become a classic to any true hip-hop fan\".<ref name=\"Gonzales\">{{cite journal |url=http://thimk.files.wordpress.com/2009/11/life-after-death-5-mics.jpg |title=Notorious B.I.G., Life After Death&nbsp;... Till Death Do Us Part (Bad Boy/Arista) |journal=[[The Source (magazine)|The Source]] |issue=92 |date=May 1997 |accessdate=October 14, 2011 |last=Gonzales |first=Michael A. |page=79}}</ref> Although [[David Browne (journalist)|David Browne]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' was unfavorable of the album's long length, and some of its violent and materialistic content, he commended Notorious B.I.G.'s \"bicoastal respect\" by working with other hip-hop styles and artists from other regions of the United States.<ref name=\"Browne\"/>\n\n=== Retrospect ===\nSince its release, ''Life After Death'' has received retrospective acclaim from critics. [[Rob Sheffield]], writing in ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]'' (2004), called it \"a [[filler (media)|filler]]-free two-disc rush of musical bravado\" and commented that the Notorious B.I.G.'s voice and lyrics were \"deeper\" than before.<ref name=\"Hoard\" /> [[AllMusic]]'s Jason Birchmeier wrote, \"It may have taken the Notorious B.I.G. a few years to follow up his milestone debut, ''Ready to Die'', with another album, but when he did return with ''Life After Death'', he did so in a huge way. The ambitious album, intended as somewhat of a sequel to ''Ready to Die'', picked up where its predecessor left off.\"<ref name=\"Birchmeier\" /> Birchmeier further said, \"Over the course of only two albums, he achieved every success imaginable, perhaps none greater than this unabashedly over-reaching success.\"<ref name=\"Birchmeier\" /> Evan McGarvey of ''[[Stylus Magazine|Stylus]]'' magazine wrote in his review, \"''Life After Death'' is a grand exercise in personal mythology, narrative sweep, and truly diverse, universal pop excellence. As a double album it is the very definition of cinematic; it essentially perfected the concept and standard in hip-hop&nbsp;... Sequenced as an unpacking of sorts, the album's progression from song to song is an essay itself.\"<ref name=\"McGarvey\">McGarvey, Evan (September 11, 2007). [http://www.stylusmagazine.com/articles/diamond/notorious-big-life-after-death.htm \"Notorious B.I.G. \u2013 Life After Death \u2013 The Diamond\"]. ''[[Stylus Magazine|Stylus]]''. Retrieved November 8, 2009.</ref> In 2013, ''VIBE'' named ''Life After Death'' the greatest Hip-Hop/R&B album since 1993.<ref name=\"album93\">[http://www.vibe.com/photo-gallery/greatest-50-albums-since-93/?page=51 The Greatest 50 Albums Since '93<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n=== Accolades ===\n*<small>The information regarding accolades is adapted from [[Acclaimed Music]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/Current/A1008.htm |title=Life After Death |website=[[Acclaimed Music]] |date= |accessdate=February 28, 2012}}</ref> except for lists that are sourced otherwise.</small>\n*<small>(*) signifies unordered lists</small>\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Publication\n! Country\n! Accolade\n! Year\n! Rank\n|-\n|''[[About.com]]''\n|[[United States]]\n|''100 Greatest Hip Hop Albums''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rap.about.com/od/toppicks/ss/Top100RapAlbums_7.htm |title=The Greatest Hip-Hop Albums of all Time |website=Rap.about.com |date=January 6, 2012 |accessdate=February 28, 2012}}</ref>\n|2008\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|40\n|-\n|''About.com''\n|United States\n|''Best Rap Albums of 1997''<ref>Adaso, Henry. [http://rap.about.com/od/top10albums/ss/90sBestRapMusic_8.htm Best Rap Albums of 1997]. about.com. Retrieved September 4, 2012-09-04.</ref>\n|2008\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|''[[Addicted to Noise]]''\n|United States\n|''Albums of the Year''\n|1997\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|7\n|-\n|''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]''\n|United States\n|''The 100 Greatest American Albums of All time''\n|2002\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|25\n|-\n|''[[Ego Trip (magazine)|Ego Trip]]''\n|United States\n|''Hip Hop's 25 Greatest Albums by Year 1980\u201398''\n|1999\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|''[[The Face (magazine)|The Face]]''\n|[[United Kingdom]]\n|''Albums of the Year''\n|1997\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|20\n|-\n|-\n|''[[Fnac]]''\n|[[France]]\n|''The 1000 Best Albums of All Time''\n|2008\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|858\n|-\n|''[[Hip Hop Connection]]''\n|United Kingdom\n|''The 100 Greatest Rap Albums 1995\u20132005''\n|2005\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|14\n|-\n|[[Tom Moon]]\n|United States\n|''[[1000 Recordings to Hear Before You Die]]''\n|2008\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|*\n|-\n|''[[The New Nation]]''\n|United Kingdom\n|Top 100 Albums by Black Artists\n|2005\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|60\n|-\n|''OOR Moordlijst''\n|[[Netherlands]]\n|''Albums of the Year''\n|1997\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|87\n|-\n|''Pure Pop''\n|[[Mexico]]\n|''Albums of the Year''\n|1997\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|18\n|-\n|''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n|United Kingdom\n|''Albums of the Year''\n|1997\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|*\n|-\n|''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n|United States\n|''[[The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time]]''\n|2012\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|476\n|-\n|''Rolling Stone''\n|United States\n|''100 Best Albums of the Nineties''<ref>[https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/100-best-albums-of-the-nineties-20110427/the-notorious-b-i-g-life-after-death-19691231 100 Best Albums of the Nineties]. ''Rolling Stone''. Retrieved September 4, 2012.</ref>\n|2011\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|66\n|-\n|''Rolling Stone''\n|United States\n|''The Essential Recordings of the 90s''\n|1999\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|*\n|-\n|''[[The Source (magazine)|The Source]]''\n|United States\n|''The 100 Best Rap Albums of All Time''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/source.htm |title=The Source 100 Best Rap Albums & Singles |website=Rocklistmusic.co.uk |date= |accessdate=February 28, 2012}}</ref>\n|2005\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|8\n|-\n|''The Source''\n|United States\n| ''The Critics Top 100 Black Music Albums of All Time''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trevornelson.com/nonflash/top100.asp |title=TOP 100 |website=Trevornelson.Com |accessdate=February 28, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120204222100/http://www.trevornelson.com/nonflash/top100.asp |archivedate=February 4, 2012 }}</ref>\n|2005\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|60\n|-\n|''[[Spex (magazine)|Spex]]''\n|[[Germany]]\n|''Albums of the Year''\n|1997\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|19\n|-\n|''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n|United States\n|''Albums of the Year''\n|1997\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|7\n|-\n|''(various writers)''\n|United States\n|'' 50 Years of Great Recordings''\n|2005\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|*\n|-\n|''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]''\n|United States\n|''51 Albums representing a Generation, a Sound and a Movement''\n|2004\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|*\n|-\n|''Vibe''\n|United States\n|''150 Albums That Define the Vibe Era (1992\u20132007)''\n|2007\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|*\n|-\n|''[[Village Voice]]''\n|United States\n|''Albums of the Year''\n|1997\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|12\n|}\n\n== Commercial performance ==\n''Life After Death'' was released to a significant amount of critical praise and commercial success. The album sold 690,000 copies in its first week.<ref>{{cite web|title=Check Out How Biggie's 'Life After Death' Was Made|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2014/03/the-making-of-life-after-death-many-men/|work=XXL |accessdate=April 15, 2014}}</ref> In 2000, the album was certified [[RIAA certification|Diamond]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=tblDiamond |title=RIAA \u2013 Gold & Platinum Database |accessdate=April 15, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130725044833/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=tblDiamond |archivedate=July 25, 2013 }}</ref> denoting shipment of 5 million copies (the threshold for double albums) and it has been credited as one of the best-selling rap albums of all time. It also made the largest jump to number one on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart in history, jumping from number 176 to number one in one week. Also, it spent four weeks at number one on the [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]] chart and topped the [[Billboard Year-End]] chart as a ''Billboard'' 200 for 1997.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/charts/yearend_chart_display.jsp?f=Top+R%26B/Hip-Hop+Albums&g=Year-end+Albums&year=1997 |title=Information Not Found |website=Billboard.com |date= |accessdate=February 28, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy and influence ==\nAlthough released in the wake of B.I.G.'s fatal shooting, ''Life After Death'' signaled a stylistic change in [[gangsta rap]] as it crossed over to the commercial mainstream. After the release of ''Life After Death'', [[Puff Daddy]]'s [[Bad Boy Records]] continued to bring pop and gangsta rap closer together: the references to violence and drug dealing remained, as did the entire \"gangsta\" rhetoric, but the overall production style changed from the previously darker sound to a cleaner, [[Sampling (music)|sample]]-heavy, more upbeat sound that was directly fashioned for the mainstream pop charts, as seen in the single \"[[Mo Money Mo Problems]]\". The Notorious B.I.G. is often credited with initiating this transition, as he was among the first mainstream rappers to produce albums with a calculated attempt to include both gritty and realistic gangsta narratives as well as more radio-friendly productions. The majority of the album was produced by [[Stevie J|Steven \"Stevie J\" Jordan]], [[Deric \"D-Dot\" Angelettie]], Carlos \"July Six\" Broady, [[Ron \"Amen-Ra\" Lawrence|Ron Lawrence]], and Nashiem Myrick. However, other notable hip-hop producers such as [[Easy Mo Bee]], [[Havoc (Mobb Deep)|Havoc]] from [[Mobb Deep]], [[DJ Premier]] and [[RZA]] from [[Wu-Tang Clan]] contributed beats to the album as well.\n\nVarious artists were specifically influenced by songs on ''Life After Death''. [[Evidence (artist)|Evidence]]'s \"Down in New York City\" is essentially \"Going Back to Cali\" from the perspective of a [[West Coast hip hop]] artist. [[Jay-Z]] borrows four bars from \"The World Is Filled...\" in his song \"[[I Just Wanna Love U (Give It 2 Me)]]\", as well as the chorus from his song \"Squeeze 1st\" from \"[[Hypnotize (The Notorious B.I.G. song)|Hypnotize]]\", a line in \"The Ruler's Back\" from \"Kick in the Door\" and \"You're Nobody ('Til Somebody Kills You)\" on \"[[D.O.A. (Death of Auto-Tune)]]\". [[Ice Cube]] borrows the chorus from \"Kick in the Door\" for his song \"Child Support\". As with B.I.G.'s \"I Love The Dough\" [[Monica (entertainer)|Monica]]'s 2010 song \"[[Everything to Me (Monica song)|Everything to Me]]\" samples \"I Love You More\" by [[Ren\u00e9 & Angela]]. The official remix includes a verse from B.I.G. that originally appeared on \"I Love The Dough\". [[SWV]] sampled \"Ten Crack Commandments\" on the opening track \"Someone\" featuring B.I.G.'s former protege and friend [[Sean Combs|Puff Daddy]]. The French rapper [[Rohff]] named his album \"La Vie Avant La Mort\" (Life Before Death) (2001) as a tribute to B.I.G, [[Joey Badass]] interpolated the lines 'Kick in the Door' on \"Super Predator\" from ''[[All-Amerikkkan Badass]]'' (2017). The album has sold 350,000 copies.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n== Track listing ==\nCredits adapted from ''Life After Death'' liner notes.<ref name=\"booklet\">[http://www.rapmusicguide.com/item/11184/Notorious_B.I.G._Life_After_Death.html Notorious B.I.G. \u2013 Life After Death: 1st Press. CD]</ref>\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = \n| headline = Disc one\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| title17 = \n| length17 = \n| title18 = \n| length18 = \n| title19 = \n| length19 = \n| title20 = \n| length20 = \n| total_length = 61:18\n| title1 = Life After Death Intro\n| writer1 = {{flat list|\n*[[The Notorious B.I.G.|Christopher Wallace]]\n*[[Sean Combs]]\n*[[Stevie J|Steven Jordan]]}}\n| extra1 = {{flat list|\n*Sean \"Puffy\" Combs\n*[[Stevie J]].\n*[[The Notorious B.I.G.