wards]]\n| [[Tony Award for Best Actor in a Play|Best Actor in a Play]]\n| ''Long Day's Journey Into Night''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| 2005\n| [[Primetime Emmy Awards]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Miniseries or a Movie|Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Miniseries or a Movie]]\n| ''Our Fathers''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2005\n| [[Satellite Awards]]\n| [[Satellite Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Series, Miniseries or Television Film|Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Series, Miniseries or Television Film]]\n| ''Our Fathers''\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Brian Dennehy}}\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* {{IMDb name|1133}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{iobdb name|18830}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070928020346/http://www.manhunter.net/the_jericho_mile_lobby_card_03.html Photograph of Dennehy as \"Doctor D.\" in Michael Mann's \"The Jericho Mile\" (1979)]\n* [http://www.broadway.com/gen/Buzz_Star_File.aspx?ci=27109 Star File: Brian Dennehy]\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Brian Dennehy\n|list =\n{{DramaDesk PlayOutstandingActor 1975-2000}}\n{{GoldenGlobeBestActorTVMiniseriesFilm 2000-2019}}\n{{OlivierAward PlayActor 2001\u20132025}}\n{{ScreenActorsGuildAward MaleTVMiniseriesMovie 1994-2009}}\n{{TonyAward PlayLeadActor}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dennehy, Brian}}\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:Chaminade High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia Lions football players]]\n[[Category:Drama Desk Award winners]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Laurence Olivier Award winners]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Bridgeport, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Bridgeport, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Tony Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Miniseries or Television Movie Actor Golden Globe winners]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Miniseries or Television Movie Screen Actors Guild Award winners]]\n[[Category:United States Marines]]\n[[Category:Yale School of Drama alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:People from Mineola, New York]]\n[[Category:American actor-athletes]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|American actor}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Brian Dennehy\n| image              = BrianDennehyJul2009.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Dennehy in July 2009\n| birth_name         = Brian Manion Dennehy\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1938|7|9}}\n| birth_place        = [[Bridgeport, Connecticut]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2020|4|15|1938|7|9}}\n| death_place        = [[New Haven, Connecticut]], U.S.\n| residence          = [[Woodstock, Connecticut]], U.S.\n| occupation         = Actor\n| years_active       = 1965\u20132020<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.registercitizen.com/news/article/Brian-Dennehy-Tony-winning-stage-screen-actor-15205508.php|title=Brian Dennehy, Tony-winning stage, screen actor, dies at 81|first1=Mark|last1=Kennedy|first2=Ap Entertainment|last2=Writer|date=April 16, 2020|website=The Register Citizen}}</ref>\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Judith Scheff|1959|1974}}<br />{{marriage|Jennifer Arnott|1988}}\n| children           = 5; including [[Elizabeth Dennehy]]\n| website            = \n}}\n\n'''Brian Manion Dennehy''' (July 9, 1938 \u2013 April 15, 2020) was an American actor of film, stage, and television. A winner of one [[Golden Globe]], two [[Tony Awards]] and a recipient of six [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nominations, he gained initial recognition in film for his role as Sheriff Will Teasle in ''[[First Blood]]'' (1982). He had roles in numerous films including ''[[Gorky Park (film)|Gorky Park]]'' (1983), ''[[Silverado (film)|Silverado]]'' (1985), ''[[Cocoon (film)|Cocoon]]'' (1985), ''[[F/X]]'' (1986), ''[[Presumed Innocent (film)|Presumed Innocent]]'' (1990), ''[[Romeo + Juliet]]'' (1996), and ''[[Knight of Cups (film)|Knight of Cups]]'' (2015). Dennehy won the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Miniseries or Television Film|Golden Globe Award for Best Actor in a Miniseries or Television Film]] for his role as [[Willy Loman]] in the television film ''[[Death of a Salesman (2000 film)|Death of a Salesman]]'' (2000).\n\nAccording to ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]],'' Dennehy was \"perhaps the foremost living interpreter\" of playwright [[Eugene O'Neill]]\u2019s works on stage and screen.  He had a decades long relationship with Chicago's [[Goodman Theatre]] where much of his O'Neill work originated.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Dagan |first=Carmel |url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/brian-dennehy-dead-dies-tommy-boy-first-blood-1234582309/ |title=Brian Dennehy, \u2018Tommy Boy\u2019 and \u2018First Blood\u2019 Star, Dies at 81 |date=2020-04-16 |work=Variety |access-date=2020-04-16 |language=en}}</ref>  He also regularly played Canada's [[Stratford Festival]], especially in works by [[William Shakespeare]] and [[Samuel Beckett]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Jones |first=Chris |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/theater/chris-jones/ct-ent-actor-brian-dennehy-dies-0417-20200416-sftbe7dzurfmfk6zcq4yzrgvry-story.html |title=Brian Dennehy, a giant of Chicago and America\u2019s stages, is dead at 81 |work=Chicago Tribune |access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBrian Manion Dennehy l<ref>{{cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:KJK7-B3Q|title=Person Details for Brian Manion Dennehy, \"United States Public Records, 1970-2009\" \u2014 FamilySearch.org}}</ref> was born on July 9, 1938 in [[Bridgeport, Connecticut]], the son of Hannah (Manion) and Edward Dennehy, a [[wire service]] editor for the [[Associated Press]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northjersey.com/community-news/grateful-that-my-parents-came-to-america-1.906633|title=Grateful that my parents came to America|author=Dennehy, Michael|work=NorthJersey.com}}</ref> He had two brothers, Michael and Edward.<ref name=filmreference>{{cite web | author= | title=Brian Dennehy Biography | url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/48/Brian-Dennehy.html | work=filmreference | year=2008 | accessdate=April 10, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | author= | title=Brian Dennehy Biography | url=https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1800026870/bio | work=Yahoo! Movies | year=2008 | accessdate=April 10, 2008}}</ref> He was of [[Irish people|Irish]] ancestry and was raised [[Catholic]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Parsi|first=Novid|url=http://chicago.timeout.com/articles/theater/81821/brian-dennehy-interview|title=Dennehy's Last Tape|work=[[Time Out (company)|Time Out]]|quote = I come from an Irish Catholic family,...|date=January 7, 2010|accessdate=June 24, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Harmetz|first=Aljean|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/04/23/movies/film-for-brian-dennehy-character-tells-all.html?pagewanted=all|title=FILM; For Brian Dennehy, Character Tells All|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 23, 1989|accessdate=June 24, 2010}}</ref> The family relocated to [[Long Island, New York]], where Dennehy attended [[Chaminade High School]] in the town of [[Mineola, New York|Mineola]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Guzm\u00e1n |first=Rafer |date=February 14, 2013 |title=Brian Dennehy returns to Long Island |url=https://www.newsday.com/entertainment/celebrities/brian-dennehy-returns-to-long-island-1.4642522 |work=[[Newsday]] |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nA football scholarship paved the way to [[Columbia University]] in New York City, where he played [[American football|football]], earned a BA in history, became a member of the [[Sigma Chi]] fraternity and played [[rugby union]] for [[Old Blue RFC]]. He went on to graduate studies in dramatic arts at [[Yale University]].  Prior to pursuing acting Dennehy worked as a stockbroker for Merrill Lynch in their Manhattan office in the mid 1970s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.college.columbia.edu/cct_archive/spr99/12a_fr.html|title=Brian Dennehy '60 \u2013 cover story|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Film===\nDennehy was primarily known as a dramatic actor. His breakthrough role was as the overzealous [[sheriff]] Will Teasle in ''[[First Blood]]'' (1982) opposite [[Sylvester Stallone]] as [[John Rambo]].\n\nHis earlier films included several comedies, like ''[[Semi-Tough]]'' with [[Burt Reynolds]] (in which he portrayed a pro football player), ''[[Foul Play (1978 film)|Foul Play]]'' with [[Chevy Chase]], and ''[[10 (film)|10]]'' with [[Dudley Moore]] (as a [[Manzanillo, Colima|Manzanillo]] bartender). He later portrayed a corrupt sheriff in the western ''[[Silverado (film)|Silverado]]'' and an [[Extraterrestrial life|alien]] in ''[[Cocoon (film)|Cocoon]]'', both released in 1985.\n\nMemorable supporting parts featured Dennehy in such films as ''[[Split Image (film)|Split Image]]'' (1982), ''[[Legal Eagles]]'' (1986), ''[[F/X]]: Murder By Illusion'' (1986), ''[[Presumed Innocent (film)|Presumed Innocent]]'' (1990), ''[[F/X2]]: The Deadly Art of Illusion'' (1991) and Prophet of Evil (1993)\n\nDennehy gradually became a valuable [[character actor]] but also achieved leading-man status in the thriller ''[[Best Seller]]'' (1987) co-starring [[James Woods]]. He also starred in the [[Peter Greenaway]] film ''[[The Belly of an Architect]]'', for which he won the Best Actor Award at the 1987 [[Chicago International Film Festival]]. Commenting upon this unusual venture, Dennehy said, \"I've been in a lot of movies but this is the first film I've made.\"\n\nHe went on to star as Harrison in the Australian film ''[[The Man from Snowy River II]]'' in 1988.\n\nOne of his most well-known roles came in the 1995 [[Chris Farley]]-[[David Spade]] comedy ''[[Tommy Boy (film)|Tommy Boy]]'' as Big Tom Callahan. He also was reunited with his ''10'' co-star [[Bo Derek]] in ''Tommy Boy'', in which she played his wife.\n\nDennehy had a voice role in the animated movie ''[[Ratatouille (film)|Ratatouille]]'' as Django, father of the rat chef Remy. He appeared as the superior officer of [[Robert De Niro]] and [[Al Pacino]] in the 2008 cop drama ''[[Righteous Kill]]'' and as the father of [[Russell Crowe]] in the 2010 suspense film ''[[The Next Three Days]]''.\n\nDennehy starred as [[Clarence Darrow]] in ''[[Alleged (film)|Alleged]]'', a film based on the [[Scopes Monkey Trial]], the famous court battle over the teaching of evolution in American public schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mlive.com/news/flint/2009/08/brian_dennehy_fred_thompson_to.html|title=Brian Dennehy, Fred Thompson to star in film shooting at Crossroads Village|first=Liz Shaw &#124; Flint|last=Journal|date=August 29, 2009|website=mlive}}</ref>\n\n===Television {{anchor|TV}}===\nDennehy began his professional acting career in small guest roles in such 1970s and 1980s series as ''[[Kojak]]'', ''[[Lou Grant (TV series)|Lou Grant]]'', ''[[Dallas (1978 TV series)|Dallas]]'', ''[[Dynasty (1981 TV series)|Dynasty]]'', and ''[[Hunter (1984 American TV series)|Hunter]]''. He also appeared in an episode of ''[[Miami Vice]]'' during the 1987\u201388 season.\n\n[[File:Brian Dennehy DF-SD-05-12671.jpg|thumb|left|Dennehy in October 2003]]\nDennehy portrayed Sergeant Ned T. \"Frozen Chosen\" Coleman in the television movie ''[[A Rumor of War (miniseries)|A Rumor of War]]'' (1980) opposite [[Brad Davis (actor)|Brad Davis]]. He continued to appear in such high-profile television films as ''[[Skokie (film)|Skokie]]'' (1981), ''[[Split Image (film)|Split Image]]'' (1982), ''[[Day One (1989 film)|Day One]]'', (1989), ''[[A Killing in a Small Town]]'' (1990) opposite [[Barbara Hershey]]. He also played the title role in [[HBO]]'s ''[[Teamster Boss: The Jackie Presser Story]]''.\n\nDennehy had a lead role as [[fire chief]]/celebrity dad Leslie \"Buddy\" Krebs in the short-lived 1982 series ''[[Star of the Family]]''. Despite his star power, that show was canceled after a half a season.\n\nDennehy was nominated for [[Emmy Awards]] six times for his television movies. He was nominated for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Miniseries or TV Movie for his performance as [[John Wayne Gacy]] in ''[[To Catch a Killer]]'', and he was nominated that same year in a different category, Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Miniseries or TV Movie, for ''The Burden of Proof'' (1992). Other Emmy nominatations were for his work in ''A Killing in a Small Town'', ''[[Murder in the Heartland]]'' (1993) and for the [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] cable TV movie ''Our Fathers'' (2005), which was about the [[Roman Catholic Church sex abuse scandal]]. In 2000, Dennehy was nominated for an Emmy for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Miniseries or TV Movie for a television presentation of his performance as [[Willy Loman]] in [[Arthur Miller]]'s ''[[Death of a Salesman]]'' which he had performed on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]]. The performance did, however, precipitate a [[Golden Globe Award]].\n\nHe starred in the popular crime drama ''[[Jack Reed (series)|Jack Reed]]'' TV movies. He also appeared as a recurring character in the [[NBC]] sitcom ''[[Just Shoot Me!]]''.\n\nDennehy was [[Parody|parodied]] in ''[[South Park: Bigger, Longer & Uncut]]'' (1999) and an episode of ''[[The Simpsons]]''.\n\nIn January 2007, he starred in the episode \"[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 8)|Scheherazade]]\" of ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]'' as a retired criminal who wants to reconnect with his daughter and admit his crimes before dying of a terminal disease thus eventually clearing a wrongfully imprisoned inmate. In April 2008, Dennehy guest-starred as a [[Teamster]] boss in [[Sandwich Day|an episode]] of ''[[30 Rock]]''.\n\nDennehy guest-starred in a 2009 episode of ''[[Rules of Engagement (TV series)|Rules of Engagement]]'' as the father of the main character, Jeff.<ref>{{cite web|title=Exclusive: Brian Dennehy Lands \"Meaty\" Sitcom Role |url=http://community.tvguide.com/blog-entry/TVGuide-News-Blog/Todays-News/Exclusive-Brian-Dennehy/800046124 |work=[[TV Guide]] |year=2008 |accessdate=September 4, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080906220125/http://community.tvguide.com/blog-entry/TVGuide-News-Blog/Todays-News/Exclusive-Brian-Dennehy/800046124 |archivedate=September 6, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nDennehy also narrated many television programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0001133/|title=Brian Dennehy's IMDB profile|accessdate=March 20, 2009}}</ref> He narrated Canadian-Irish docudrama ''[[Death or Canada]]''.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.rte.ie/arts/2009/0108/ifta.html|title=IFTA nominations for Farrell & Gleeson |date= January 8, 2009|accessdate=January 8, 2009|publisher=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RT\u00c9]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.thestar.com/Entertainment/article/601265|title=Brian Dennehy narrates film on Toronto's role in Irish famine| date= March 12, 2009|accessdate=March 20, 2009 | work=The Star | first=Victoria | last=Ahearn}}</ref>\n\nDennehy was set to star in the [[Amazon Studios]] series ''Cocked'' which will costar [[Jason Lee (actor)|Jason Lee]], [[Dreama Walker]], [[Diora Baird]], and [[Sam Trammell]].\n\nDennehy starred as Elizabeth Keen's grandfather on the NBC series ''[[The Blacklist (TV series)|The Blacklist]]''.\n\n===Theater===\nDennehy won two [[Tony Awards]], both times for Best Lead Actor in a Play. The first win was for ''[[Death of a Salesman]]'' (for which he also won a [[Laurence Olivier Award]] for the production's London run), in 1999, and the second was for [[Eugene O'Neill]]'s ''[[Long Day's Journey into Night]]'' in 2003. Both productions were directed by [[Robert Falls]] and were originally produced at the [[Goodman Theatre]] company in [[Chicago]].\n\nOn stage, Dennehy made frequent performances in the Chicago theater world, and made his Broadway debut in 1995 in [[Brian Friel]]'s ''[[Translations]]''. In 1999, he was the first male performer to be voted the [[Sarah Siddons Award]] for his work in [[Theatre in Chicago|Chicago theater]]. He made a return to Broadway in 2007 as Matthew Harrison Brady in ''[[Inherit the Wind (play)|Inherit the Wind]]'' opposite [[Christopher Plummer]], then returned again opposite [[Carla Gugino]] in a 2009 revival of [[Eugene O'Neill]]'s [[Desire Under the Elms]].\n\nIn fall 1992, he played the lead role of Hickey in Robert Falls's production of [[Eugene O'Neill]]'s ''[[The Iceman Cometh]]'' at the [[Abbey Theatre]] in Dublin.<ref name=\"irishtimes-bull\" />\n\nIn 2008, Dennehy appeared at the [[Stratford Shakespeare Festival]], in Stratford, Ontario, Canada, appearing in ''[[All's Well That Ends Well]]'' as the King of France, and a double bill of plays, [[Samuel Beckett]]'s ''[[Krapp's Last Tape]]'' and Eugene O'Neill's ''[[Hughie]]'', where Dennehy reprised the role of Erie Smith.\n\nIn 2010, he was inducted into the [[American Theatre Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/146911-Theater-Hall-of-Fame-Ceremony-Honoring-Linda-Lavin-Brian-Dennehy-Michael-Blakemore-Presented-Jan-24 |title=Theater Hall of Fame Ceremony, Honoring Linda Lavin, Brian Dennehy, Michael Blakemore, Presented Jan. 24 |work=Playbill |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222204659/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/146911-Theater-Hall-of-Fame-Ceremony-Honoring-Linda-Lavin-Brian-Dennehy-Michael-Blakemore-Presented-Jan-24 |archivedate=February 22, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2010, he returned to Ireland to play Bull McCabe in the [[Olympia Theatre (Dublin)|Olympia Theatre]] of [[Dublin]]'s stage version of [[John B. Keane]]'s ''[[The Field (play)|The Field]]''.<ref name=\"irishtimes-bull\">\n{{Cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/weekend/2011/0108/1224287012018.html|title=The Bull in winter|publisher=The Irish Times | date=January 1, 2011}}\n</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/weekend/2011/0122/1224288049876.html|title=Real-life dramas? We don't do those. But John B Keane did|author=Fintan O'Toole|publisher=The Irish Times|date=January 1, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/arts/the-ignoble-passions-of-the-field-fail-to-ignite-2507559.html|title=The ignoble passions of The Field fail to ignite|author=Emer O'Kelly|publisher=Independent.ie|date=January 23, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Dennehy returned to the [[Stratford Shakespeare Festival]] in the role of Sir Toby Belch in Shakespeare's ''[[Twelfth Night]]''. He also played Max in [[Harold Pinter]]'s ''[[The Homecoming]]'', the first Pinter work to be produced there.<ref>{{cite news | work = New York Times | access-date = April 16, 2020 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/03/theater/brian-dennehy-at-stratford-shakespeare-festival.html | date= September 2, 2011 | title = Brian Dennehy as a Troublemaker, Times Two | first = Charles | last = Isherwood}}</ref>\n\nIn April through June 2012, he played the role of Larry Slade in the [[Eugene O'Neill]] play ''[[The Iceman Cometh]]'' at the [[Goodman Theatre]] in Chicago,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/robert-bullen/iceman-cometh-play_b_1484561.html | work=Huffington Post | first=Robert | last=Bullen | title=Goodman's Iceman Cometh, Starring Nathan Lane, Chills to the Core | date=May 8, 2012}}</ref> which he reprised in 2015 when the production, with most of the Goodman Theater production cast, was revived at the BAM Harvey Theater in Brooklyn, New York.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/13/theater/review-the-iceman-cometh-revived-with-nathan-lane-and-brian-dennehy.html?_r=0 | work=New York Times | first=Charles | last=Isherwood | title=Review: 'The Iceman Cometh' Revived, With Nathan Lane and Brian Dennehy | date=February 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the comic book series ''[[Ultimate Spider-Man]]'', that [[Alternative versions of the Green Goblin|series' version]] of the villain [[Norman Osborn]] was rendered by artist [[Mark Bagley]] to resemble actor Brian Dennehy, as per writer [[Brian Michael Bendis]]' instructions.<ref name=WizardXtra>Brucie, Dylan (March 2007). \"Ultimate Spider-Man\". ''[[Wizard (magazine)|Wizard Xtra!]]''. p. 117.</ref>\n\n==Personal life and death==\nDennehy enlisted in the [[United States Marine Corps]] from 1958 to 1963, including a brief stint on [[Okinawa]]. In a 1989 interview he described being hurt in combat and in 1993 he told an interviewer he had served in Vietnam. He apologized for misrepresenting his military record in 1999.<ref>{{cite news | access-date = April 16, 2020 | work= Financial Times | url = https://www.ft.com/content/17939f78-2263-11d9-be80-00000e2511c8 | date= October 22, 2004 | title= Mock Heroics | first = Jonathan | last = Green}}</ref>\n\nHe married twice and had five children including actress [[Elizabeth Dennehy]].<ref>{{cite web |date=July 10, 2012 |title=Where Are They Now? TNG Guest Star Elizabeth Dennehy |publisher=StarTrek.com |url=http://www.startrek.com/article/where-are-they-now-tng-guest-star-elizabeth-dennehy |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDennehy died on April 15, 2020, of cardiac arrest due to sepsis at his home in [[New Haven, Connecticut]].<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/theater/chris-jones/ct-ent-actor-brian-dennehy-dies-0417-20200416-sftbe7dzurfmfk6zcq4yzrgvry-story.html | title = Brian Dennehy, a giant of Chicago and America\u2019s stages, is dead at 81 | first = Chris | last = Jones | work = Chicago Tribune | date= April 16,  2020 | access-date = April 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/16/movies/brian-dennehy-dead.html | title = Brian Dennehy Dies; Tony Award-Winning Actor Was 81 | first =Derrick Bryson | last =Taylor  | work = New York Times  | date= April 16, 2020 | access-date = April 16, 2020}}</ref> He was 81 years old.\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 1977\n| ''Bumpers''\n| Ernie Stapp\n| TV movie\n|-\n| 1977\n| ''[[Looking for Mr. Goodbar (film)|Looking for Mr. Goodbar]]''\n| Surgeon\n|\n|-\n| 1977\n| ''[[Semi-Tough]]''\n| T.J. Lambert\n|\n|-\n| 1978\n| ''[[F.I.S.T.]]''\n| Frank Vasco\n|\n|-\n| 1978\n| ''[[Foul Play (1978 film)|Foul Play]]''\n| Fergie\n|\n|-\n| 1979\n| ''[[Butch and Sundance: The Early Days]]''\n| O.C. Hanks\n|\n|-\n| 1979\n| ''[[10 (film)|10]]''\n| Don the Bartender\n|\n|-\n| 1980\n| ''[[Little Miss Marker (1980 film)|Little Miss Marker]]''\n| Herbie\n|\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[Split Image (film)|Split Image]]''\n| Kevin Stetson\n|\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[First Blood]]''\n| Sheriff Will Teasle\n|\n|-\n| 1983\n| ''[[Never Cry Wolf (film)|Never Cry Wolf]]''\n| Rose Little\n|\n|-\n| 1983\n| ''[[Gorky Park (film)|Gorky Park]]''\n| William Kirwill\n|\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[Finders Keepers (1984 film)|Finders Keepers]]''\n| Mayor Frizzoli\n|\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[The River Rat]]''\n| Doc Cole\n|\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[Cocoon (film)|Cocoon]]''\n| Walter\n|\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[Silverado (film)|Silverado]]''\n| Sheriff Cobb\n|\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[Twice in a Lifetime (film)|Twice in a Lifetime]]''\n| Nick\n|\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[F/X]]''\n| Lt. Leo McCarthy\n|\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''The Check Is in the Mail''\n| Richard Jackson\n|\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Legal Eagles]]''\n| C.J. Cavanaugh\n|\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''[[The Belly of an Architect]]''\n| Stourley Kracklite\n|\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''[[Best Seller]]''\n| Lt. Dennis Meechum\n|\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[The Man from Snowy River II]]''\n| Harrison\n|\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[Miles from Home]]''\n| Frank Roberts, Sr.\n|\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[Cocoon: The Return]]''\n| Walter\n| Uncredited role\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[:Indio (1989 film)|Indio]]''\n| Whytaker\n|\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''{{ill|Seven Minutes (1989 film)|de|3=Georg Elser \u2013 Einer aus Deutschland|lt=Seven Minutes}}''\n| Wagner\n|\n|-\n| 1990\n| ''[[The Last of the Finest|Blue Heat]]''\n| Frank Daly\n| aka The Last of the Finest\n|-\n| 1990\n| ''[[Presumed Innocent (film)|Presumed Innocent]]''\n| Raymond Horgan\n|\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''[[F/X2]]''\n| Leo McCarthy\n|\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Gladiator (1992 film)|Gladiator]]''\n| Jimmy Horn\n|\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''Jackaboy Blue''\n| Guggles McMillian\n|\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[Tommy Boy (film)|Tommy Boy]]''\n| Big Tom Callahan II\n|\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[The Stars Fell on Henrietta]]''\n| Big Dave McDermot\n|\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Romeo + Juliet]]''\n| Ted Montague\n|\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[The Virtuoso]]''\n| Unknown\n|\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''Out of the Cold''\n| David Bards\n|\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''Silicon Towers''\n| Tom Warner\n|\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[Dish Dogs]]''\n| Frost\n|\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Summer Catch]]''\n| John Schiffner\n|\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[Stolen Summer]]''\n| Father Kelly\n|\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''Code Yellow: Hospital at Ground Zero''\n| Narrator\n|\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''Drawing First Blood''\n| Himself\n| Short\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[She Hate Me]]''\n| Chairman Billy Church\n|\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Assault on Precinct 13 (2005 film)|Assault on Precinct 13]]''\n| Jasper O'Shea\n|\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''Tommy Boy: Behind the Laughter''\n| Himself\n| Short\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[10th and Wolf]]''\n| Agent Horvath\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Everyone's Hero]]''\n| Babe Ruth\n| Voice\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[The Ultimate Gift]]''\n| Gus\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Ratatouille (film)|Ratatouille]]''\n| Django\n| Voice\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''Welcome to Paradise''\n| Bobby Brown\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[War Eagle, Arkansas (film)|War Eagle, Arkansas]]''\n| Pop\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''Cat City''\n| Harold Vogessor\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Righteous Kill]]''\n| Lt. Hingus\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''Factory 9''\n| Unknown\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Every Day (2010 film)|Every Day]]''\n| Ernie\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Meet Monica Velour]]''\n| Pop Pop\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[The Next Three Days]]''\n| George Brennan\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Alleged (film)|Alleged]]''\n| Clarence Darrow\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[The Big Year]]''\n| Raymond Harris\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''Twelfth Night''\n| Sir Toby Belch\n|\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[The Challenger]]''\n| Chairman William Rogers\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Knight of Cups (film)|Knight of Cups]]''\n| Joseph\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[The Seagull (2018 film)|The Seagull]]''\n| Sorin\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Tag (2018 film)|Tag]]''\n| Randy's Father\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''The Song of Sway Lake''\n| Hal Sway\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''Driveways''\n| Del\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''Master Maggie''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://filmthreat.com/reviews/master-maggie/|title=Master Maggie &#124; Film Threat|date=August 14, 2019}}</ref>\n| Himself\n| Short\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''3 Days With Dad''\n| Bob Mills\n|\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Son of the South (film)|Son of the South]]''\n| Grandfather\n| ''Post-production'', Posthumous release \n|-\n| TBA\n| ''Long Day Journey'' \n|\n| ''Post-production'', Posthumous release; Final film role\n|}\n\n===Television films===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 1977\n| ''Johnny, We Hardly Knew Ye''\n| Longshoreman\n|\n|-\n| 1977\n| ''[[It Happened at Lakewood Manor]]''\n| Fire Chief\n|\n|-\n| 1978\n| ''[[A Real American Hero (TV movie)|A Real American Hero]]''\n| Buford Pusser\n|\n|-\n| 1978\n| ''[[Ruby and Oswald]]''\n| George Paulsen\n|\n|-\n| 1978\n| ''[[A Death in Canaan]]''\n| Barney Parsons\n|\n|-\n| 1979\n| ''[[Dummy (1979 film)|Dummy]]''\n| Ragoti\n|\n|-\n| 1979\n| ''[[The Jericho Mile]]''\n| Dr. D\n|\n|-\n| 1979\n| ''Silent Victory: The Kitty O'Neil Story''\n| Mr. O'Neil\n|\n|-\n| 1980\n| ''[[A Rumor of War (miniseries)|A Rumor of War]]''\n| Sgt. Ned Coleman\n|\n|-\n| 1980\n| ''The Seduction of Miss Leona''\n| Bliss Dawson\n|\n|-\n| 1981\n| ''[[Skokie (film)|Skokie]]''\n| Chief Arthur Buchanan\n|\n|-\n| 1981\n| ''Fly Away Home''\n| Tim Arnold\n|\n|-\n| 1