ategory:Drama Desk Award winners]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Laurence Olivier Award winners]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Bridgeport, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Bridgeport, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Tony Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Miniseries or Television Movie Actor Golden Globe winners]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Miniseries or Television Movie Screen Actors Guild Award winners]]\n[[Category:United States Marines]]\n[[Category:Yale School of Drama alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:People from Mineola, New York]]\n[[Category:American actor-athletes]]\n", "name_user": "Bmclaughlin9", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brian_Dennehy"}
{"title_page": "Michel Band", "text_new": "The '''Michel Band''', or formerly, [http://www.michelfirstnation.com/ The Michel First Nation], is an [[Indigenous peoples in Canada|Indigenous]] group of people located central [[Alberta]], [[Canada]]. Named after the first elected council Chief, Michel Callihoo, the band officially signed [[Treaty 6|Treaty Number 6]] by adhesion on September 3rd of 1878. The Michel First Nation is comprised primarily of [[Iroquois]], [[Cree]] and [[M\u00e9tis]] with over 700 current registered descendants. <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Macpherson|first=Elizabeth|title=The Sun Traveller|publisher=Mus\u00e9e H\u00e9ritage Museum|year=1998|isbn=|location=St.Albert, Alberta|pages=6}}</ref> \n[[File:Numbered-Treaties-Map.svg|thumb|Numbered-Treaties-Map]]\nThe Michel [[First nations reserve|Reserve]] #132 was once located near the present-day town site of [[Villeneuve, Alberta|Villenevue]], Alberta, described and surveyed in September 1880 by G.A. Simpson; \"to a post on the right bank of the Sturgeon River and thence easterly along the said bank of the river to the point of beginning, containing an area of forty square miles more or less.\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=MacPherson|first=Elizabeth|title=The Sun Traveller|publisher=Mus\u00e9e H\u00e9ritage Museum|year=1998|isbn=|location=St.Albert, Alberta|pages=56}}</ref> \n\nThe entire band was illegally [https://www.ictinc.ca/blog/indian-act-and-enfranchisement-of-indigenous-peoples enfranchised] by the Canadian Government on March 31 1958 by Order in Council P.C. 375. The Michel First Nation is the only band in [[Canada]] during the 20th Century to be enfranchised. <ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Iroquois History==\nThe Michel Band emerged as a distinct cultural and [[kinship]] group during the [[North American fur trade|Canadian Fur Trade]], traveling west from the [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] [[Iroquois]] communities of [[Caughnawaga Indian Village Site|Caughnawaga]] and [[St. Regis Mohawk Reservation|St.Regis]]. Generations of Iroquois had been trapping furs for a living and had become relatively dependent on trade goods to maintain a comfortable lifestyle in the [[Saint Lawrence River|St.Lawrence River]] and [[Great Lakes region|Great Lakes regions]]. <ref name=\":0\" /> \n[[File:Iroquois_western_goods.jpg|thumb|Iroquois, with western goods 1722]]\n\nPrior to their divergence as distinct Catholic communities, most Iroquois were politically governed by the traditional customs and governance of the [[Great Law of Peace]]. In 1645 Iroquois [[Tribal chief|headmen]] began treating the [[French people|Frenchmen]] of [[Trois-Rivi\u00e8res]], the [[Wyandot people|Hurons]], and [[Algonquins]]. In their dealings with the French, Iroquois diplomats adapted the language and rituals of the Great Law of Peace to create the protocol for intercultural diplomacy.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Richter|first=Daniel K.|title=Beyond the Covenant Chain: The Iroquois and Their Neighbors in Indian North America, 1600-1800|publisher=Penn State Press|year=November 1, 2010|isbn=|location=|pages=22}}</ref>In 1654, [[Daniel Garaconti\u00e9|Daniel Garakontie]] or \"The Moving Sun\" was the [[Sachem|Great Sachem]] of the Iroquois Confederacy.<blockquote>\"Five whole Nations address thee through my mouth. I have in my heart the sentiments of all the Iroquois Nations - and my tongue is faithful to my heart.\" -Garakontie<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Jesuits|first=|title=Jesuit Relations|publisher=Burrows Bros. Co|year=1896|isbn=|location=Cleveland|pages=53:45}}</ref></blockquote>Garakontie was known as ''Sagochiendagehte'' (\"the name bearer\") the Council name of the Onondaga - a status he occupied as its principal speaker. Garakontie was his family name and not his [[Hereditary title|hereditary]] title, thus his status as speaker and chief diplomat was achieved, not ascribed by his membership into the [https://www.haudenosauneeconfederacy.com/clan-system/ Bear Clan]. <ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Fenton|first=William Nelson|title=The Great Law and the Longhouse: A Political History of the Iroquois Confederacy|publisher=University of Oklahoma|year=1998|isbn=|location=|pages=285}}</ref> The first references to Garakonti\u00e9 reveal him struggling to preserve the general peace of 1653.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/garakontie_1E.html|title=Daniel Garakontie|last=|first=|date=|website=Dictionary of Canadian Biography|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>  \n\nWhile in Quebec Garakontie proclaimed his faith in Christianity.<ref name=\":2\" /> Garakonti\u00e9 was baptized in the Cathedral of Quebec. <ref name=\":3\" />  He announced he would no longer sponsor dream feasts and declared the Iroquois cosmology was a fable. <ref name=\":1\" /> Traditionalist Iroquois headmen maintained that Garakontie had become French and untrustworthy<ref name=\":2\" />The Jesuits had not only created Catholic converts, but also strong Christian and Traditionalist factions that brought unprecedented disquiet to Iroquois communities.. <ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=Hackett|first=David G.|title=Religion and American Culture: A Reader|publisher=Psychology Press|year=2003|isbn=|location=|pages=64}}</ref>\n\nBy the late 1660's Jesuit missionaries encouraged increasing numbers of Catholic Iroquois to desert their homes for the [[Christian mission|mission]] villages in Canada; by the mid 1670's over two-hundred had departed. The lack of pelts to trade and warfare created serious economic hardship in Iroquoia. In 1700, over 500 of their 2000 warriors had been killed, captured, or had deserted to Catholic missions. <ref name=\":4\" />\n\n= Louis Kwarakwante =\n[[File:Fur_traders_in_canada_1777.jpg|thumb|Fur traders in canada 1777]]Louis Kwarakwante (\"The Sun Traveller\") was born in 1782 near the Catholic Mission of Saul St. Louis of [[Caughnawaga Indian Village Site|Caughnawaga]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Morin|first=Gail|title=Company Men: Louis Callihoo|publisher=Gail Morin|year=2019|isbn=|location=|pages=1}}</ref> It is speculated that Louis was [[Mohawk people|Mohawk]]. The name Kwarakwante appears to be an incorrect translation of Garakontie. Records list his surname variously as \"Karaconti. Karaquienthe, Caraquanti.\" Louis also went by the surname of Callihoo, which derived from \"Karhioo\" meaning  \"Tall Forest\" in Iroquois. Many members of his family, especially those who went west with the Fur Trade, had the name Karakontie bestowed on them by the [[clergy]]. Louis Kwarakwante was likely a grandson of [[Daniel Garaconti\u00e9|Daniel Garakontie]].<ref name=\":0\" />[[File:Canoe_Manned_by_Voyageurs_Passing_a_Waterfall.jpg|thumb|Canoe Manned by Voyageurs Passing a Waterfall]]\n\nAs early as 1800, the [[North West Company]] began to employ Iroquois [[Voyageurs|voyagers]]. [[Colin Robertson (fur trader)|Colin Robertson]] said he preferred the Iroquois voyageurs to French-Canadians in a rapid or dangerous river crossing \"for their calmness and presence of mind which never forsakes them in the greatest danger.\" <ref name=\":0\" />This was still a common trend even up until 1872, when George Grant remarked:<blockquote>\"Our crews were chiefly Iroquois Indians from Caugh-naw-aga, near Montreal, the best voyagers known, according to the testimony of everyone who has tried them. The Iroquois made the engagement for the trip, and hired a few Ojibways bear the Shebandowan and Fort Francis to make up the necessary number. They were as fine-looking, clean-limbed men as one's eye could desire to rest on, punctual, diligent, uncomplaining, and reserving their chief affection for their canoes. As a jockey cherishes his horse and  shepherd his dog, so do they care for their canoe.\" <ref>{{Cite book|last=George|first=Grant|title=By Canoe From Toronto To Fort Edmonton in 1872: Among The Iroquois and Ojibways with a chapter on Winter in Canada|publisher=Canadiana House Toronto|year=1968|isbn=|location=Toronto|pages=}}</ref>  </blockquote>The NWC undoubtedly hired Iroquois from Caughnawaga not only for their experience, but also their familiarity with the Catholic clergy and the [https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/seigneurial-system habitant seigneuries] who had land holdings in the Missions. The Regardless, the bark [[Longhouses of the indigenous peoples of North America|longhouses]] still resembled those of in Mohawk Valley, and [[Three Sisters (agriculture)|traditional agriculture]] was still practiced. In this Mission, Louis Callihoo learned his [[catechism]] and his [[Prayer|prayers]] in his [[Iroquoian languages|native tongue]]. He spoke French and later many other languages as well, which no doubt made his commercial dealings easier. He was contracted as a canoemen on November 23 1800 by McTavish, Frobisher & Company, agents of the NWC. \n\n= Iroquois Freeman =\n[[File:Winter_couriers_of_the_North-West_Fur_Company_from_Victor.png|thumb|Winter couriers of the North-West Fur Company ]]\n[[File:A_M\u00e9tis_man_and_his_two_wives,_circa_1825-1826.jpg|thumb|A M\u00e9tis man and his two wives, circa 1825-1826]]\n{{First Nations in Alberta}}\n{{Numbertreaty|treaty=6}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:First Nations history in the District of Alberta]]\n[[Category:M\u00e9tis in Alberta]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of M\u00e9tis descent|*]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Mohawk descent|*]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Cree descent|*]]\n[[Category:Franco-Albertan culture]]\n[[Category:Government agencies disestablished in 1958]]\n[[Category:1958 disestablishments in Canada]]\n[[Category:First Nations in Alberta]]\n[[Category:Sekani people|*]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Michel Band''', or formerly, [http://www.michelfirstnation.com/ The Michel First Nation], is an [[Indigenous peoples in Canada|Indigenous]] group of people located central [[Alberta]], [[Canada]]. Named after the first elected council Chief, Michel Callihoo, the band officially signed [[Treaty 6|Treaty Number 6]] by adhesion on September 3rd of 1878. The Michel First Nation is comprised primarily of [[Iroquois]], [[Cree]] and [[M\u00e9tis]] with over 700 current registered descendants. <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Macpherson|first=Elizabeth|title=The Sun Traveller|publisher=Mus\u00e9e H\u00e9ritage Museum|year=1998|isbn=|location=St.Albert, Alberta|pages=6}}</ref> \n[[File:Numbered-Treaties-Map.svg|thumb|Numbered-Treaties-Map]]\nThe Michel [[First nations reserve|Reserve]] #132 was once located near the present-day town site of [[Villeneuve, Alberta|Villenevue]], Alberta, described and surveyed in September 1880 by G.A. Simpson; \"to a post on the right bank of the Sturgeon River and thence easterly along the said bank of the river to the point of beginning, containing an area of forty square miles more or less.\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=MacPherson|first=Elizabeth|title=The Sun Traveller|publisher=Mus\u00e9e H\u00e9ritage Museum|year=1998|isbn=|location=St.Albert, Alberta|pages=56}}</ref> \n\nThe entire band was illegally [https://www.ictinc.ca/blog/indian-act-and-enfranchisement-of-indigenous-peoples enfranchised] by the Canadian Government on March 31 1958 by Order in Council P.C. 375. The Michel First Nation is the only band in [[Canada]] during the 20th Century to be enfranchised. <ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Iroquois History==\nThe Michel Band emerged as a distinct cultural and [[kinship]] group during the [[North American fur trade|Canadian Fur Trade]], traveling west from the [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] [[Iroquois]] communities of [[Caughnawaga Indian Village Site|Caughnawaga]] and [[St. Regis Mohawk Reservation|St.Regis]]. Generations of Iroquois had been trapping furs for a living and had become relatively dependent on trade goods to maintain a comfortable lifestyle in the [[Saint Lawrence River|St.Lawrence River]] and [[Great Lakes region|Great Lakes regions]]. <ref name=\":0\" /> \n[[File:Iroquois_western_goods.jpg|thumb|Iroquois, with western goods 1722]]\n\nPrior to their divergence as distinct Catholic communities, most Iroquois were politically governed by the traditional customs and governance of the [[Great Law of Peace]]. In 1645 Iroquois [[Tribal chief|headmen]] began treating the [[French people|Frenchmen]] of [[Trois-Rivi\u00e8res]], the [[Wyandot people|Hurons]], and [[Algonquins]]. In their dealings with the French, Iroquois diplomats adapted the language and rituals of the Great Law of Peace to create the protocol for intercultural diplomacy.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Richter|first=Daniel K.|title=Beyond the Covenant Chain: The Iroquois and Their Neighbors in Indian North America, 1600-1800|publisher=Penn State Press|year=November 1, 2010|isbn=|location=|pages=22}}</ref>In 1654, [[Daniel Garaconti\u00e9|Daniel Garakontie]] or \"The Moving Sun\" was the [[Sachem|Great Sachem]] of the The Iroquois Confederacy.<blockquote>\"Five whole Nations address thee through my mouth. I have in my heart the sentiments of all the Iroquois Nations - and my tongue is faithful to my heart.\" -Garakontie<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Jesuits|first=|title=Jesuit Relations|publisher=Burrows Bros. Co|year=1896|isbn=|location=Cleveland|pages=53:45}}</ref></blockquote>Garakontie was known as ''Sagochiendagehte'' (\"the name bearer\") the Council name of the Onondaga - a status he occupied as its principal speaker. Garakontie was his family name and not his [[Hereditary title|hereditary]] title, thus his status as speaker and chief diplomat was achieved, not ascribed by his membership into the [https://www.haudenosauneeconfederacy.com/clan-system/ Bear Clan]. <ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Fenton|first=William Nelson|title=The Great Law and the Longhouse: A Political History of the Iroquois Confederacy|publisher=University of Oklahoma|year=1998|isbn=|location=|pages=285}}</ref> The first references to Garakonti\u00e9 reveal him struggling to preserve the general peace of 1653.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/garakontie_1E.html|title=Daniel Garakontie|last=|first=|date=|website=Dictionary of Canadian Biography|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>  \n\nWhile in Quebec Garakontie proclaimed his faith in Christianity.<ref name=\":2\" /> Garakonti\u00e9 was baptized in the Cathedral of Quebec. <ref name=\":3\" />  He announced he would no longer sponsor dream feasts and declared the Iroquois cosmology was a fable. <ref name=\":1\" /> Traditionalist Iroquois headmen maintained that Garakontie had become French and untrustworthy<ref name=\":2\" />The Jesuits had not only created Catholic converts, but also strong Christian and Traditionalist factions that brought unprecedented disquiet to Iroquois communities.. <ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=Hackett|first=David G.|title=Religion and American Culture: A Reader|publisher=Psychology Press|year=2003|isbn=|location=|pages=64}}</ref>\n\nBy the late 1660's Jesuit missionaries encouraged increasing numbers of Catholic Iroquois to desert their homes for the [[Christian mission|mission]] villages in Canada; by the mid 1670's over two-hundred had departed. The lack of pelts to trade and warfare created serious economic hardship in Iroquoia. In 1700, over 500 of their 2000 warriors had been killed, captured, or had deserted to Catholic missions. <ref name=\":4\" />\n\n= Louis Kwarakwante =\n[[File:Fur_traders_in_canada_1777.jpg|thumb|Fur traders in canada 1777]]Louis Kwarakwante (\"The Sun Traveller\") was born in 1782 near the Catholic Mission of Saul St. Louis of [[Caughnawaga Indian Village Site|Caughnawaga]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Morin|first=Gail|title=Company Men: Louis Callihoo|publisher=Gail Morin|year=2019|isbn=|location=|pages=1}}</ref> It is speculated that Louis was [[Mohawk people|Mohawk]]. The name Kwarakwante appears to be an incorrect translation of Garakontie. Records list his surname variously as \"Karaconti. Karaquienthe, Caraquanti.\" Louis also went by the surname of Callihoo, which derived from \"Karhioo\" meaning  \"Tall Forest\" in Iroquois. Many members of his family, especially those who went west with the Fur Trade, had the name Karakontie bestowed on them by the [[clergy]]. Louis Kwarakwante was likely a grandson of [[Daniel Garaconti\u00e9|Daniel Garakontie]].<ref name=\":0\" />[[File:Canoe_Manned_by_Voyageurs_Passing_a_Waterfall.jpg|thumb|Canoe Manned by Voyageurs Passing a Waterfall]]\n\nAs early as 1800, the [[North West Company]] began to employ Iroquois [[Voyageurs|voyagers]]. [[Colin Robertson (fur trader)|Colin Robertson]] said he preferred the Iroquois voyageurs to French-Canadians in a rapid or dangerous river crossing \"for their calmness and presence of mind which never forsakes them in the greatest danger.\" <ref name=\":0\" />This was still a common trend even up until 1872, when George Grant remarked:<blockquote>\"Our crews were chiefly Iroquois Indians from Caugh-naw-aga, near Montreal, the best voyagers known, according to the testimony of everyone who has tried them. The Iroquois made the engagement for the trip, and hired a few Ojibways bear the Shebandowan and Fort Francis to make up the necessary number. They were as fine-looking, clean-limbed men as one's eye could desire to rest on, punctual, diligent, uncomplaining, and reserving their chief affection for their canoes. As a jockey cherishes his horse and  shepherd his dog, so do they care for their canoe.\" <ref>{{Cite book|last=George|first=Grant|title=By Canoe From Toronto To Fort Edmonton in 1872: Among The Iroquois and Ojibways with a chapter on Winter in Canada|publisher=Canadiana House Toronto|year=1968|isbn=|location=Toronto|pages=}}</ref>  </blockquote>The NWC undoubtedly hired Iroquois from Caughnawaga not only for their experience, but also their familiarity with the Catholic clergy and the [https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/seigneurial-system habitant seigneuries] who had land holdings in the Missions. The Regardless, the bark [[Longhouses of the indigenous peoples of North America|longhouses]] still resembled those of in Mohawk Valley, and [[Three Sisters (agriculture)|traditional agriculture]] was still practiced. In this Mission, Louis Callihoo learned his [[catechism]] and his [[Prayer|prayers]] in his [[Iroquoian languages|native tongue]]. He spoke French and later many other languages as well, which no doubt made his commercial dealings easier. He was contracted as a canoemen on November 23 1800 by McTavish, Frobisher & Company, agents of the NWC. \n\n= Iroquois Freeman =\n[[File:Winter_couriers_of_the_North-West_Fur_Company_from_Victor.png|thumb|Winter couriers of the North-West Fur Company ]]\n[[File:A_M\u00e9tis_man_and_his_two_wives,_circa_1825-1826.jpg|thumb|A M\u00e9tis man and his two wives, circa 1825-1826]]\n{{First Nations in Alberta}}\n{{Numbertreaty|treaty=6}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:First Nations history in the District of Alberta]]\n[[Category:M\u00e9tis in Alberta]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of M\u00e9tis descent|*]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Mohawk descent|*]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Cree descent|*]]\n[[Category:Franco-Albertan culture]]\n[[Category:Government agencies disestablished in 1958]]\n[[Category:1958 disestablishments in Canada]]\n[[Category:First Nations in Alberta]]\n[[Category:Sekani people|*]]\n", "name_user": "Ira Leviton", "label": "safe", "comment": "Deleted a duplicate \"the\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michel_Band"}
